Approach: Tumor specimens were acquired from 505 women with Luminal A breast cancer who went through breast-conserving surgery, with endocrine therapy following. The women were NOT treated with whole-breast radiation, and were monitored for disease recurrence, new primary cancer and survival. The tumor specimens were studied with Ki-67 IHC, with study participants all having a Ki-67 index <= 13.25%. 
Figure 1. (A) Representative image of randomly selected virtual (tissue microarray-equivalent) 1-mm cores. Software-generated random virtual 1-mm circles (shown in red, with a number inside) are identified within the tumour area (enclosed by a yellow line), previously defined by the scoring pathologist. To generate the random virtual cores, a rectangle enclosing the entire tumour area is first defined. A pair of randomly selected x and y coordinates (along the width and height of this rectangle, respectively) is generated. A square is then defined by the following four coordinates: [x,y], [x + d,y], [x,y + d], [x + d,y + d], where d is the diameter (pixel equivalent of 1 mm). If the two points [x, y] and [x + d,y + d] both fall within the tumour area, this square is considered to be within the tumour area. A virtual tissue microarray core to be used for Ki67 scoring is then defined as the smallest circle enclosing the two points [x,y] and [x + d,y + d]. The random seed that was used to generate the x/y coordinates is recorded in the data file to ensure that, if needed, the same sequence of random virtual core images can be reproduced for reassessment. (B) Virtual core being presented to the scoring pathologist for nuclei counting;
